sp.p:
Now, by Clotho’s own spindle, my questions are free from all sophistic taint. How it has come about, I know not;




but one word has brought up another, and the end of it is—
there is no use in sacrifice. Let us begin again. I will put you a few more questions; answer me frankly, but think before you speak, this time.

The full absurdity of the thing is seen in the case of Latus:
Seek not for offspring in the Gods’ despite;
Beget a child, and thou begett’st thy slayer. Was not this advice superfluous, seeing that the end must come? Accordingly we find that the oracle does not deter Laius from begetting a son, nor that son from being his slayer. On the whole, I cannot see that your prophegies entitle you to reward.
